Ensemble Learning Project: EasyVisa¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

def plot_distributions_with_target(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Plots distributions and boxplots of a predictor variable with respect to a target variable.

    Parameters:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The dataset containing the predictor and target variables.
        predictor (str): The name of the predictor variable.
        target (str): The name of the target variable.

    Returns:
        None
    """
    # Create a grid of subplots
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    # Extract unique values of the target variable
    unique_targets = data[target].unique()

    # Plot distribution for the first unique target value
    axs[0, 0].set_title(f"Distribution for target = {unique_targets[0]}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == unique_targets[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    # Plot distribution for the second unique target value
    axs[0, 1].set_title(f"Distribution for target = {unique_targets[1]}")
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == unique_targets[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    # Plot a boxplot with outliers
    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot with Outliers")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="coolwarm")

    # Plot a boxplot without outliers
    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot Without Outliers")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="coolwarm",
    )

    # Adjust layout for better visibility
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [78]:
def plot_stacked_bar(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Displays category counts and visualizes a stacked bar chart showing the distribution
    of the target variable across the predictor categories.

    Parameters:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The dataset containing the predictor and target variables.
        predictor (str): The independent variable (categorical).
        target (str): The dependent (target) variable.

    Returns:
        None
    """
    # Calculate the number of unique predictor categories
    unique_count = data[predictor].nunique()

    # Identify the target category with the smallest count
    least_common_target = data[target].value_counts().idxmin()

    # Create and display a cross-tab for category counts
    category_counts = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True)
    category_counts = category_counts.sort_values(by=least_common_target, ascending=False)
    print("Category Counts:\n", category_counts)
    print("-" * 100)

    # Normalize the cross-tab by row to compute percentages
    normalized_tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index")
    normalized_tab = normalized_tab.sort_values(by=least_common_target, ascending=False)

    # Plot the stacked bar chart
    normalized_tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(unique_count + 5, 5), colormap="viridis")
    plt.title(f"Stacked Bar Chart of {target} Across {predictor} Categories")
    plt.xlabel(predictor.capitalize())
    plt.ylabel("Proportion")
    plt.legend(title=target, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left", frameon=False)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

  • Jobs in the Midwest and South regions yield higher approval ratios compared to those in the Northeast, West, and especially the Island region.

Model building¶

Model Evaluation Criteria:¶

The model may produce two types of incorrect predictions:¶
  • Predicting an applicant will be approved when they are actually denied.
  • Predicting an applicant will be denied when they are actually approved.
Which case is more critical?¶

Both scenarios have significant implications:

  • Approving an unqualified applicant means a job intended for a U.S. citizen may be wrongly assigned.
  • Denying a qualified applicant prevents U.S. companies from filling vital positions, potentially impacting economic productivity.
How to minimize losses?¶
  • Given the resource-intensive nature of application reviews, the model should prioritize identifying candidates likely to be approved, enabling agents to focus on these cases.
  • The F1 Score is an appropriate evaluation metric, as it balances precision and recall, helping reduce both False Positives and False Negatives.
  • Using balanced class weights ensures the model gives equal attention to both approval and denial cases, maintaining fairness in predictions.

Defining functions to for performance metric scores (i.e., accuracy, recall, and precision) and confusion matrix on the train and test datasets.¶

In [94]:
# defining a function to compute performance metrics of classification model
def classification_model_perf_metrics(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [107]:
def confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Tuning XGB Classifer¶

In [162]:
#classifier. 
xgb_tuned = XGBClassifier(random_state=1, eval_metric='logloss')

#parameters to choose
parameters = {"n_estimators": np.arange(10,100,20),
              "scale_pos_weight":[0,1,2,5],
              "subsample":[0.5,0.7,0.9,1],
              "learning_rate":[0.01,0.1,0.2,0.05],
              "gamma":[0,1,3],
              "colsample_bytree":[0.5,0.7,0.9,1],
              "colsample_bylevel":[0.5,0.7,0.9,1]}

# compare parameter combinations with scorer
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the randomized search
r_xgb = RandomizedSearchCV(xgb_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer,cv=5, n_jobs=-1, random_state=1)
r_xgb = r_xgb.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
xgb_tuned = r_xgb.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
xgb_tuned.fit(x_train, y_train)

Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Profile of Applicants Likely to Receive Visa Approval¶
Ideal Profile Characteristics:¶
  • Education Level: Higher education is advantageous. Applicants with at least a Bachelor’s degree are more likely to be approved, with those holding a Master’s or Doctorate degree having the highest chances.
  • Job Experience: Prior work experience significantly boosts approval chances.
  • Prevailing Wage: The median wage for certified visa applicants is approximately $72,000 annually.
Additional Factors to Consider:¶
  • Unit of Wage: Yearly wages are more commonly associated with approved applications.
  • Continent: Applicants originating from Europe, Africa, and Asia tend to have higher visa approval rates.
Profile of Applicants Likely to Have Visa Denied¶
Key Characteristics:¶
  • Education Level: Applicants with only a high school education or no degree at all face higher chances of rejection.
  • Job Experience: Lack of any prior work experience is a strong factor in denial.
  • Prevailing Wage: The median wage for denied applicants is lower, around $65,000 annually.
Additional Factors to Consider:¶

Unit of Wage: Applications with hourly wages are more frequently denied.

Recommendations for Further Insights¶

To enhance understanding and improve visa decision-making, collecting additional data is essential:¶
Employer-Specific Data:¶
  • Wage structures offered to applicants.
  • Industry or sector the employer operates in.
Employee-Specific Data:¶
  • Specializations within educational qualifications.
  • Detailed records of job experience, including years and roles.
